Its called the spread operator, what it does is copy everything in the object its put into. For example. 
let dontMutateThisArray = [a,b,c,d,e,f,g];
  lets say we wanna make a copy and mutate it. 
let shouldIMutateThis = dontMutateThisArray;
I want to change a copy of this array but it is a refrence type meaning if we did  change this array it will change the original array anyway because the copied variable is just pointing still to the original variable. Thus changing what you might have thought was a different object. 
shouldIMutateThis.slice(0, 1);
will change dontMutateThisArray 
So to make a true copy that has nothing to do with the original use ...objectToBeCopied
For this example we are using an array so
 let iCanMutateThisSafely = [...dontMutateThisArray];
Now you can do whatever you want and maintain the original, this is the way all functional programming should be done, preserve the original and mutate the copy. 
